<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-admin-password-reset-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Resetting the admin password, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qb-help-admin-password-reset-in-brief-text">The QuickBooks <em>admin</em> login is the master account &mdash; the one with full access to the company file and every user&rsquo;s permissions. Resetting its password is a legitimate, documented process, but it works differently in each product. In <strong>QuickBooks Desktop</strong>, the admin password is local to the company file, and QuickBooks provides an Automated Password Reset path that verifies you through the Intuit email and license your software is registered under, then lets you set a new password. In <strong>QuickBooks Online</strong>, there is no separate &ldquo;QuickBooks password&rdquo; &mdash; the admin password is your <strong>Intuit account</strong> password, so you reset it through Intuit&rsquo;s ordinary &ldquo;I forgot my password&rdquo; recovery, the same way you would for any Intuit product.</p>
      <p>In both products the gate is the same: Intuit (or QuickBooks&rsquo; reset tool, which checks against your registered Intuit account) has to confirm you are the rightful owner before any password changes. That is by design, and it is what keeps your books out of the wrong hands. It also means an independent firm genuinely <em>cannot</em> do this for you &mdash; we have no access to your Intuit account, your login, or your password, and we would never claim to. What we <em>can</em> do begins after you&rsquo;re back in: rebuilding a tangled Desktop user list, and repairing books that fell behind while access was lost.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

